lesson_name: Developing Fluency Using 2 as a Factor
transcript:
Server Notice @ [2018-09-19T17:52:16.838Z]: This conversation will be saved.
Server Notice @ [2018-09-19T17:52:16.841Z]: Your device supports Web RTC audio
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:52:16.846Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:52:28.818Z]: type
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:52:46.934Z]: Ok! Let's get started!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:53:09.112Z]: Let's talk about the word equivalent!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:53:15.784Z]: Any idea what that might mean?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:53:27.133Z]: noooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooooo
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:53:44.682Z]: Well, that is a good place to start then! : )
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:04.615Z]: Equivalent sounds a lot like another word we use in math- equal!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:13.634Z]: What does equal mean?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:54:21.163Z]: smae
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:54:25.738Z]: same
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:28.533Z]: Yep!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:38.578Z]: If something is equivalent, it has the same value!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:43.506Z]: It's worth the same amount!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:55.467Z]: 10 pennies is equivalent to 1 dime.
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:54:58.461Z]: Make sense?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:55:04.425Z]: yesssssssss
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:55:21.147Z]: Great! So...what is the value of 3 x 4?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:55:40.536Z]: 16
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:56:04.404Z]: Check your facts if you need to and try again! I know you've got this!
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:56:06.975Z]: 12
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:56:11.040Z]: YES!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:56:49.135Z]: So... 3 x 4 is equivalent to 12
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:57:01.747Z]: is 3 x 4 equivalent to 2 x 6?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:57:17.872Z]: 12
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:57:37.573Z]: Yes! Both have a value of 12, so they are equivalent!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:57:42.205Z]: Let's go back to the problem here!
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:58:06.335Z]: okay
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:58:20.392Z]: What is the value of 2 x 4 + 4?
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:58:55.237Z]: solve it for me!
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:59:32.539Z]: 15
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:59:46.764Z]: Let's break it apart together! What is 2 x 4?
Carlos @ [2018-09-19T17:59:59.304Z]: 12

Server Notice @ [2018-09-19T17:38:09.616Z]: This conversation will be saved.
Server Notice @ [2018-09-19T17:38:09.617Z]: Your device supports Web RTC audio
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:38:09.618Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:38:25.718Z]: Hi,type
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:38:40.679Z]: Ok, great!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:38:44.832Z]: Let's take a look!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:39:07.859Z]: When we say something is proportional, can you explain in your own words what proportional means?
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:40:23.771Z]: I really like the octopus example in your hints by the way! : )
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:40:27.600Z]: It helps me visualize
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:40:40.599Z]: it is  something that have the same ratios,size or amount
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:40:47.351Z]: that is true!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:41:07.976Z]: so, no matter how many times the quantity changes, the ratio is still the same.
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:41:34.190Z]: So...1 octopus has 2 eyes for every 8 arms.
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:41:37.929Z]: 2/8
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:42:02.899Z]: what do 2 octopus have? what is the ratio there?
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:42:51.860Z]: 4 eyes for every 16 arms so 4/16
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:43:11.290Z]: yes! Is 2/8 equal to 4/16? Is it proportional?
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:43:20.156Z]: yes
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:43:54.395Z]: You are right! They key is that no matter how many octopus we add, this will remain constant.
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:44:10.459Z]: There will not all of a sudden be an octopus with 3 eyes : )
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:44:27.978Z]: right
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:44:41.710Z]: So, looking at your answer choices here, which of these scenarios will remain consistent no matter what?
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:45:33.179Z]: your seed while riding a roller coaster
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:46:32.973Z]: Does the rate of speed change on a roller coaster?
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:46:41.582Z]: Think about going up a hill vs. going down a hill
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:46:54.447Z]: oh
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:47:09.899Z]: right! It's not a constant, unchanging rate of speed.
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:47:34.975Z]: a car ride at a constant rate speed of 25 mph for 8 mins/
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:47:40.534Z]: Bingo!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:47:48.214Z]: That is the only constant rate given
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:48:12.539Z]: so the proportion between time and distance will always remain the same, no matter how many miles we travel!
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:48:19.569Z]: yes
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:48:39.530Z]: I think you are ready to tackle the next one on your own! What do you think?
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:49:04.145Z]: yea i'm ready
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:49:10.335Z]: Great job today!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-19T17:49:12.616Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
Jaquelyn @ [2018-09-19T17:49:22.826Z]: ok bye

lesson_name: Comparing Fractions with Different Numerators and Different Denominators
transcript:
Server Notice @ [2018-09-18T17:49:36.081Z]: This conversation will be saved.
Server Notice @ [2018-09-18T17:49:36.084Z]: Your device supports Web RTC audio
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:49:36.088Z]: Hi! Let's look over your problem again. Would you like me to type or talk?
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:50:04.550Z]: Hi Ms.Desiree I love your Unique name
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:50:13.931Z]: Why, thank you!
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:50:25.072Z]: Your Very Welcom
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:50:27.720Z]: Are you ready?!
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:50:28.498Z]: e
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:50:30.339Z]: Yes
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:50:45.052Z]: YESSSSSSSSSSS
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:50:47.195Z]: Great!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:51:02.020Z]: Let's take a look at this problem together!
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:51:11.931Z]: YE$ ma'm
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:51:36.650Z]: One way we can think about fractions is to break a whole into pieces!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:51:47.604Z]: Pizza is easy to think about : )
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:52:03.378Z]: I am hungry now but yes
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:52:06.404Z]: Let's imagine breaking a pizza into 12 slices : )
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:52:09.697Z]: Ok
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:52:20.024Z]: If we eat 5 of them, have we eaten half of the pizza?
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:53:03.606Z]: No ma'm if the Pizza was 10 peices we would have ate half of the pizza 12 is not 10 and 10 is not 12
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:53:31.825Z]: Very good! So we know that 5/12 is LESS THAN 1/2.
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:53:41.445Z]: YE$
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:53:51.407Z]: Now, what if we had 10 slices, and ate 7? Less than or more than half?
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:54:06.370Z]: More then Half
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:54:27.617Z]: Yes! So, that is one way we can compare two fractions as given in this problem!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:54:34.579Z]: Which fraction is greater?
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:54:36.607Z]: YE
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:54:42.636Z]: S
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:54:50.908Z]: Um 7/10
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:55:11.317Z]: Am I correct???
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:55:15.849Z]: You've got it, Emma! I think you could do the next problem on your own! Do you have any other questions?
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:55:55.822Z]: THANK$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$ And no questions (the yes was for getting it right)
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:56:14.705Z]: YES!!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:56:36.878Z]: Great! Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
Emma @ [2018-09-18T17:56:38.858Z]: Bye thank you for everything :) :) :) :) :)
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-18T17:56:43.098Z]: Sure!

Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:46:36.310Z]: x, y

Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:46:52.091Z]: So, now how would you change your last answer!

Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:47:44.071Z]: very good. If I buy .45 lbs of almonds, how much will I pay?
NATALY @ [2018-09-17T17:48:09.968Z]: 2.3
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:48:31.446Z]: Very nice! So...
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:48:49.259Z]: what do I mean when I say 'Unit rate?'
NATALY @ [2018-09-17T17:49:05.896Z]: the amount by time
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:49:34.928Z]: It COULD be by time- such as how long it takes me to drive 1 mile.
NATALY @ [2018-09-17T17:49:49.564Z]: Yes
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:49:52.072Z]: Or it could be measured by weight/price as in this problem!
Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:50:03.246Z]: How do we find the unit rate? What operation might we use?
NATALY @ [2018-09-17T17:50:23.130Z]: Yea so it’s 2.3/0.45

Ms. Desiree @ [2018-09-17T17:51:00.769Z]: Please come back if you need more help. Have a nice day!
